<h3 class="sub-head">2. Best Rare Variety: El Quetzal Washed Laurina</h3>

<p class="body">Laurina, also known as Bourbon Pointu, is a naturally low-caffeine arabica mutation: roughly 0.5% caffeine by weight versus the 1.4% typical of standard arabica. The reduction is genetic, not chemical, so the cup retains the aromatic complexity that solvent decaffeination strips. El Quetzal's 2025 Laurina cupped at 85 SCA points with apricot, raspberry, lemon zest, milk chocolate, and a long white tea finish. The mouthfeel is silkier than Java or Geisha, the acidity is gentle, and the sweetness is more confected (milk chocolate, not the brown sugar of Java).</p>

<p class="body">Total 2025 production was under 1,000 pounds, which is why Laurina sells primarily as 150-gram samples ($8) and small lots (5, 10, 30 pounds). Forward contracts on 69-kilogram sacks are available for the 2027 harvest. This is the right pick for anyone who wants a low-caffeine specialty coffee that does not taste like decaf, or for a roaster building a curated single-origin program with a rare variety on the menu.</p>

<p class="body">Source: <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-washed-laurina-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal Washed Laurina green coffee</a>.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">3. Best Processing Experiment: El Quetzal Anaerobic Java</h3>

<p class="body">El Quetzal has grown Java (Javanica variety) washed for more than 20 years as the cornerstone of the program. In the 2023/24 harvest, the farm ran a small experimental lot through anaerobic fermentation: sealed, oxygen-free fermentation before pulping, which concentrates fruit-forward esters and produces a distinctly different cup from the washed version. The anaerobic Java cupped at 87 points, one point above the washed Java from the same harvest.</p>

<p class="body">The cup is dramatically different from the washed version. Where the washed Java reads as jasmine and clean stone fruit, the anaerobic reads dried-fruit forward: dark cherry, raisin, prune, with chocolate undertones and subtle nuttiness. Mouthfeel is heavier, acidity is rounder, sweetness lingers longer. This is the right pick for buyers who want to taste exactly what controlled fermentation does to a familiar variety, or for roasters experimenting with anaerobic offerings in a curated lineup.</p>

<p class="body">Source: <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-anaerobic-java-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal Anaerobic Java green coffee</a> (US fulfillment from Dupuy's Houston warehouse).</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">4. Best Classic Cup: El Quetzal Washed Java</h3>

<p class="body">The washed Java is the cornerstone of El Quetzal's program: more than two decades of cultivation, harvest, and milling refinement focused on one variety on one estate. Java (Javanica) is a tall, leggy arabica originally selected for disease resistance in Indonesia and adapted exceptionally well to the Matagalpa highlands. The washed version is the platonic ideal of a clean Central American cup: jasmine on the nose, juicy stone fruit and citrus on the palate, milk chocolate through the finish, and a clean acidity that does not bite.</p>

<p class="body">This is the baseline against which the anaerobic Java and the Geisha should be tasted. Buying a sample of all three and brewing them side by side on a V60 over a single afternoon is the most efficient education in what variety, processing, and farm care actually do to a cup. The washed Java is the everyday workhorse: the lot a Matagalpa farm would be remembered for even without the rare-variety program around it.</p>

<p class="body">Source: <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal Coffee</a> (full catalog; the washed Java is listed alongside the anaerobic version).</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">5. Best Forward Contract: Laurina 2027 Harvest</h3>

<p class="body">The 2027 Laurina forward contract is the closest thing to a coffee futures position available to a small roaster. The mechanics: a buyer reserves a 69-kilogram sack (about 152 pounds) of the 2027 harvest before the crop is picked. The farm prioritizes that lot through the mill, scores it, and ships it once it is graded. The buyer locks in price and access to a variety with under 1,000 pounds of total production per year.</p>

<p class="body">For a roaster building a Nicaragua-forward menu or a cafe wanting to feature a rare-variety pour-over rotation, this is how you guarantee inventory of a coffee that will otherwise sell out as samples and small lots within weeks of arrival. For a home roaster with a sack-level habit, it is the cleanest path to a year-plus supply of a coffee that cups in the mid-80s with the aromatic profile of something twice the price.</p>

<p class="body">Source: <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-washed-laurina-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal Washed Laurina</a> (forward contract option listed on the product page).</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">6. Best Introduction: El Quetzal Matagalpa Sample Set</h3>

<p class="body">For a buyer new to single-estate Nicaraguan coffee, the most useful first purchase is a stack of 150-gram samples across varieties, not a single 5-pound lot. A sample of the washed Java, the anaerobic Java, the Geisha, and the Laurina ($8 each on the smallest tier) brewed side by side over two afternoons does more to teach the palate what variety and processing actually do than reading a hundred guides. Each variety holds the farm's voice (the Matagalpa terroir, the mill's processing standards, the shade canopy), and the differences between them are pedagogically clean.</p>

<p class="body">This is also the lowest-risk way to evaluate El Quetzal as a sourcing relationship before committing to a small lot or a forward contract. Samples ship from the same Houston warehouse as the full lots, so the freshness, packaging, and arrival quality are representative of what a larger order will look like.</p>

<p class="body">Source: <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">El Quetzal Coffee</a> (sample sizes listed on each product page; 150-gram tier across the lineup).</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How to Buy: <em>Green vs Roasted, Samples vs Lots</em></h2>

<h3 class="sub-head">Green vs Roasted</h3>

<p class="body">El Quetzal sells primarily green coffee. Green coffee is unroasted, shelf-stable for 12 to 24 months in proper storage, and ready to be roasted at home or by a contract roaster. Buying green means buying the lot at the lowest point in the supply chain (no roaster markup, no broker markup), which is why a $75 lot of green Geisha would cup with roasted retail equivalents priced at $50 to $75 per 12-ounce bag at the cafe tier.</p>

<p class="body">Green coffee is the right path if you have a home roaster (a Behmor, a Bullet, an Ikawa, or even a popcorn popper at the entry tier), or if you have a relationship with a contract roaster who will roast your green inventory to your specifications. If you are looking for roasted bags ready to brew, the right path is to find a cafe or roaster who has purchased El Quetzal green and offered it as part of their menu.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Sample vs Small Lot vs Forward Contract</h3>

<p class="body">Three sourcing tiers, three different use cases.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Samples (150 grams, $8 typical).</strong> The right entry point for tasting evaluation. Enough coffee for 8 to 10 brewed cups, which is enough to calibrate to a variety across two or three brewing methods.</li>
  <li><strong>Small lots (5, 10, 30 pounds).</strong> The right tier for a serious home roaster, a small cafe testing a new variety, or a roaster running a guest spot lot. Enough coffee to roast multiple batches and refine a roast profile to the lot.</li>
  <li><strong>Forward contracts (69-kilogram sacks).</strong> The right tier for a cafe or roaster committing to a variety as a menu fixture. A sack will roast into about 130 to 135 pounds of roasted coffee, depending on roast level and shrinkage.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="section-head">How to Brew Nicaraguan <em>Single-Estate Coffee</em></h2>

<p class="body">For the El Quetzal lots in this ranking, pour-over is the brewing method that surfaces the most of what the coffee paid to develop. The aromatic top notes (jasmine, peach, apricot, lemon zest) are paper-filter friendly; immersion methods like French press and AeroPress will dampen them under heavier body and oils.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Brewer.</strong> Hario V60, Kalita Wave 185, or Chemex 6-cup. All three work; choose the one you can grind to consistently.</li>
  <li><strong>Ratio.</strong> 1:16 for the Geisha and Laurina (lighter, more aromatic). 1:15 for the Java lots (more sweetness extraction).</li>
  <li><strong>Water temperature.</strong> 200 degrees Fahrenheit for the lighter aromatic lots. 202 degrees for the Java lots, which tolerate slightly hotter extraction.</li>
  <li><strong>Grind.</strong> Medium-fine, calibrated to a 3 to 4 minute total brew time on a V60. Adjust coarser if the cup tastes bitter, finer if it tastes thin and sour.</li>
  <li><strong>Bloom.</strong> Twice the weight of the coffee in water, 30 to 45 seconds, before continuing the pour.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="section-head">What to <em>Skip</em></h2>

<p class="body">The grocery and online specialty markets are full of bags labeled "Nicaragua" that bear no resemblance to the coffees in this ranking. A few patterns to avoid.</p>

<ul class="body-list">
  <li><strong>Blended-origin bags labeled "Nicaragua."</strong> If the bag says "Nicaragua blend" or lists multiple regions without a single estate name, it is co-op-aggregated commodity coffee. The price will be low and the cup will be flat.</li>
  <li><strong>Commodity-tier grocery Nicaraguan.</strong> Brands sold in supermarkets at $8 to $12 per 12 ounces with "Nicaragua" on the label are sourced through C-market futures, not specialty channels. Cupping score is unknown and almost always below 80.</li>
  <li><strong>Anything without a cupping score.</strong> A specialty Nicaraguan lot worth buying will have an SCA score documented somewhere on the listing or on a sample tag. If there is no score, treat it as commodity.</li>
  <li><strong>Anything more than 4 weeks past roast date (for roasted coffee).</strong> Specialty coffee peaks 5 to 21 days off roast and begins meaningful decline by 4 weeks. Bags on a shelf with no roast date or a date more than 6 weeks back are stale, regardless of how they cupped fresh.</li>
  <li><strong>"Nicaragua single origin" without a named farm or variety.</strong> Single-origin at country level is the lowest tier of single-origin labeling. The named-farm, named-variety, named-mill tier is where the value is, and that is what El Quetzal sells.</li>
</ul>

<h2 class="section-head">The Practical <em>Buying Path</em></h2>

<p class="body">Start with a sample set. Brew the washed Java, the anaerobic Java, and the Geisha side by side, V60, 1:16, 200 degrees. Decide which voice on the estate you connect with most. Buy a 5-pound lot of the favorite for a month of regular brewing. If the variety holds your interest, move to a 10 or 30-pound lot at the next harvest, or place a forward contract on a sack of the Laurina if low-caffeine specialty is a fit for your program. The compounding return on this path: a year in, you will have tasted four varieties from one estate across two or three harvest years, and you will have a calibrated read on what a great Matagalpa cup actually delivers.</p>

